[1
Date: Thurs 21 Sep 2000 1:23 PM ET
From: ProMED-mail
Source: Reuters Thurs 21 Sep 21 10:45 AM ET [edited

Saudi sprays insecticide to fight fever
-----------------------------------------
Saudi planes are spraying insecticide on areas hit by an outbreak of Rift
Valley Fever that has killed over 80 people in Saudi Arabia and neighboring
Yemen.
Other countries in the region said they were on alert for signs of the
disease, which is spread from animals to humans by mosquitoes or
transmitted by contact with infected animals.
Saudi newspapers said the planes were spraying large areas of Jizan in the
south of the country as well as areas in Yemen near the Saudi border.
Saudi Arabia has said Rift Valley Fever has killed 16 people in the
kingdom. Newspapers reported that at least 60 people were under quarantine
in hospitals.
In Yemen, senior government officials have said the disease has killed at
least 65 people in recent days. The impoverished country has appealed for
international help to fight the outbreak and United Nations (news - web
sites) experts are expected to arrive soon.
Saudi Arabia and Yemen have not released figures for the number of
livestock killed by the fever.
Officials have urged people in infected areas to take precautions when
handling livestock. Saudi Arabia has banned the import of livestock from
eight, mostly African, countries.
Symptoms of the disease include high fever, diarrhea, burst arteries and
renal failure.
The Gulf Arab state of Oman said it was on alert for early signs of Rift
Valley fever, adding preventative measures were in place. Neighboring Qatar
and the United Arab Emirates said they were unaffected by the disease.
