[4
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Date: Thu, 21 Sep 2000 14:11:26 GMT
Source: Agence France Presse, 21 Sep 2000 [edited

Sudan fears big losses from Saudi livestock ban over disease
------------------------------------------------------------
Sudanese exporters feared Thursday they will suffer "big losses" from Saudi
Arabia's ban on livestock imports from African countries after 16 Saudis
died of Rift Valley Fever this month.
Government officials, who insisted that Sudan was free of the disease,
added here that Khartoum and Riyadh had made ministerial-level contacts
concerning the ban, newspapers reported.
Saudi officials announced Monday that they had decided to suspend imports
of livestock from Djibouti, Ethiopia, Eritrea, Somalia, Sudan and Yemen,
where they could be infected.
Sudan's Livestock Exporters Association was assessing the Saudi decision.
"This surprise decision by Saudi Arabia banning Sudanese livestock exports
will cause big losses to Sudanese exporters," Association Chairman Siddeiq
Haidub was Thursday quoted by independent Al Ayam daily as saying.
Hundreds of thousands of head of sheep and other livestock, including goats
and cattle, are exported annually to Saudi Arabia, Sudan's biggest market.
Haidub said exporters had asked their agents in the livestock production
areas in western Sudan, such as Kurdofan, to stop purchasing and sending
the livestock to Khartoum for export.
"There are now large numbers of head of livestock ready for shipment
abroad, a matter which will cost the exporters a great deal," Haidub said.
Meanwhile, Animal Resources Minister Abdallah Sidahmed told a cabinet
meeting on Wednesday that international organisations "did not indicate the
existence of this disease in the country," the official Al Anbaa daily said.
The cabinet's economic council, however, instructed the authorities to take
measures to ensure that Sudan is free of Rift Valley Fever and that the
country's livestock is not infected.
Saudi Arabia's health ministry said Sunday that the fever was first
reported September 11 in Jizan province, bordering Yemen, and that 16 of
the 36 people infected by it have died.
It was believed to have been introduced to Saudi Arabia via sheep, a large
number of which have recently died in Jizan, according to the health ministry.
It is the first time that the disease, which affects domestic animals and
can be transmitted to humans by mosquitoes, has been known to strike
outside Africa.
Symptoms include hemorrhagic fever, encephalitis and eye problems, although
human deaths from the disease are rare, according to experts.
Since Rift Valley Fever was first identified in 1930 after an epidemic
among sheep in Kenya, it has also affected Egypt, Madagascar, Mauritania
and Somalia, according to the World Health Organization.
