[The first 3 reports are examples of vector control measures being
implemented along with heightened awareness of the disease and increased
surveillance in neighboring countries.
The last article is a good example of the economic impact of disease
outbreaks that can affect import and export markets, especially when the
food chain is involved. As has been illustrated in numerous ProMED-mail
postings, an initial reaction of many countries is to ban the movement of
potentially infected animals across borders. In this case, the livestock
industry of Sudan is being impacted purely by virtue of Sudan's
geographical location on the African continent, even though the disease has
not been officially reported from the Sudan (albeit it has been reported
from it's neighbors, Egypt to the north and Kenya to the South). This
major economic
impact of disease outbreaks should clearly demonstrate to countries the
importance of early identification and recognition of disease transmission
with rapid implementation of control measures. - Mod.MPP
[RVF is a peracute or acute zoonotic disease of domestic ruminants in
Africa. Signs of the disease tend to be nonspecific, rendering it
difficult to recognize individual cases. During epidemics, the occurrence
of numerous abortions and deaths among young animal, together with an
influenza-like disease in man, tends to be characteristic.
The incubation period is 12-36 hours in lambs. A biphasic fever of up to
41C may develop, and affected animals are listless and not inclined to
move or feed and may show signs of abdominal pain. Lambs usually die
within 2 days. Older animals may die acutely or develop an inapparent
infection. Sick animals may regurgitate, develop icterus, and an unusually
bad-smelling diarrhea. Sometimes, abortion may be the only sign of
infection. In pregnant ewes, the mortality and abortion rates vary from 5
to almost 100 percent in different outbreaks and on different farms. The
rates in cattle are generally less than 10 percent.
Immunization remains the only effective way to protect livestock. Although
some times of immunization may cause abortion, pregnant ewes may be
considered for vaccination with a formalin inactivated form of virus.
People involved in the livestock industry should be made aware of the
potential dangers of exposure to RVF-infected animals and tissues. The
use of protective clothing and treatment with immune plasma and the
antiviral drug ribavirin should be considered when necessary. - Mod.TG
